WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.960
Okay, hello everybody. My name is Gabe Osterhout. I'm the data viz guy for the

00:00:04.960 --> 00:00:08.560
Idaho Secretary of State. So as my title suggests, I work for the Secretary of

00:00:08.560 --> 00:00:13.400
State, like him himself, and by his title he's the chief election official for the

00:00:13.400 --> 00:00:18.400
state of Idaho. So we have many roles in our office that we provide to the state,

00:00:18.400 --> 00:00:22.360
but one of those is on election night, you know, when you're getting your results

00:00:22.360 --> 00:00:26.760
from CNN, the New York Times, if you're going to the state's direct website, you

00:00:26.760 --> 00:00:29.879
know, we're the ones who aggregate that data. So usually when you vote, at least

00:00:29.879 --> 00:00:33.599
in a state like Idaho, the county administers the election, kind of at the

00:00:33.599 --> 00:00:36.279
precinct of the polling place, they report the results to the county and the

00:00:36.279 --> 00:00:39.400
county's reporting it to us. So on election night, we're the ones

00:00:39.400 --> 00:00:42.619
responsible for aggregating that information and then publishing it so

00:00:42.619 --> 00:00:47.680
the public can see it and then the media can grab that data as well. So we tried

00:00:47.680 --> 00:00:51.520
something new for the 2024 elections where we used R & Quarto for that

00:00:51.520 --> 00:01:03.439
process. Remember the 2020 election? It was not a fun time, you know. I was, we

00:01:03.439 --> 00:01:08.360
were not in office during the 2020 election, thankfully, but, you know, my boss

00:01:08.360 --> 00:01:14.480
took office in 2023 and my my position actually didn't exist yet. There was no

00:01:14.480 --> 00:01:18.080
data visualization person, there was no data analyst person in our office, believe

00:01:18.080 --> 00:01:21.959
it or not, but my boss, thankfully, is a data nerd. I don't know how many of you

00:01:21.959 --> 00:01:26.720
work for data nerds, but it's very nice to have allies in powerful places, but

00:01:26.720 --> 00:01:29.919
this was kind of the world that we took office in, right? There were still a lot

00:01:29.919 --> 00:01:35.040
of the the consequences of the 2020 election, a lot of conspiracy theories,

00:01:35.040 --> 00:01:39.800
misinformation, you know, valid or not, this was kind of the world we are working

00:01:39.800 --> 00:01:48.360
in. So everything election related in my world is extremely scrutinized. So going

00:01:48.360 --> 00:01:52.080
into the 2024 election, we have kind of these ghosts of 2020 in our head, right?

00:01:52.080 --> 00:01:57.919
Even though we didn't work the election. And so at the beginning of 2024, we

00:01:57.919 --> 00:02:02.400
launched this great new voteidaho.gov website. It recently won an award. It was

00:02:02.400 --> 00:02:07.080
highly acclaimed at the time. Voters really liked it. It became a one-stop

00:02:07.080 --> 00:02:10.639
shop for all kinds of voter information. Check your polling place, view your

00:02:10.639 --> 00:02:16.440
sample ballot, and, you know, we thought, hey, this is 2024, we're entering the

00:02:16.440 --> 00:02:19.080
cycle, they have all these great resources. Why not also make it a

00:02:19.080 --> 00:02:25.759
one-stop shop for election results on election night? So my kind of role in all

00:02:25.759 --> 00:02:29.080
of this, obviously, is, all right, so now I'm tasked with improving our election

00:02:29.080 --> 00:02:39.800
results for 2024. Can't be that difficult. So my boss, he wanted to kind

00:02:39.800 --> 00:02:42.839
of remind me, you know, we have a lot of things going on in the data visualization

00:02:42.839 --> 00:02:46.279
world. As we all kind of know, there's competing priorities, there's lots of

00:02:46.279 --> 00:02:49.960
questions that are super interesting to me. Now that we've kind of got a bunch of

00:02:49.960 --> 00:02:53.279
dashboards and visuals and insight into past elections, since my position never

00:02:53.279 --> 00:02:56.880
existed, there's a ton of outside interest in media questions, questions

00:02:56.880 --> 00:03:00.279
in the legislature, like, what about this? What about that? And unfortunately, one of

00:03:00.279 --> 00:03:02.520
my weaknesses is, well, that sounds really interesting, I want to pursue that

00:03:02.520 --> 00:03:06.600
question, too. But we had this real time constraint, right? We're not operating in

00:03:06.600 --> 00:03:09.520
a vacuum where we have time to do everything. So, you know, my boss is

00:03:09.520 --> 00:03:12.360
worried about me getting distracted, so he put this priority list on my desk.

00:03:12.360 --> 00:03:15.600
Election results were the second most important thing I could be working on at

00:03:15.600 --> 00:03:18.199
all times. It was also the third most important thing, the fourth most

00:03:18.199 --> 00:03:22.440
important thing, and fifth, sixth, and seventh. So it's helpful for me. I just

00:03:22.440 --> 00:03:26.320
kind of show you this as a reminder of, all right, this is kind of an

00:03:26.320 --> 00:03:31.000
important thing. We can't screw it up, obviously, right, given what happened in

00:03:31.000 --> 00:03:38.080
2020. Not that anybody screwed anything up, but it would just kind of, you know,

00:03:38.080 --> 00:03:41.800
reinforce those fears people had. Oh, see, you know, there were mistakes. I've been

00:03:41.800 --> 00:03:45.839
saying that all along. We really want to avoid that. But it was also helpful when

00:03:45.839 --> 00:03:50.199
these requests came out or came into our office. I could just show them, hey, you

00:03:50.199 --> 00:03:56.800
know, the boss says focus on election results. So as I'm thinking about ways

00:03:56.800 --> 00:03:59.960
to improve our election results, you know, we're looking at what other states are

00:03:59.960 --> 00:04:07.559
doing. Now, election night reporting, I'll call it ENR as an acronym, it, you know,

00:04:07.559 --> 00:04:11.800
every state does it. It's always been secure. It's always been accurate, as a

00:04:11.800 --> 00:04:14.759
lot of us know, but the data visualization part of it for other

00:04:14.759 --> 00:04:18.600
states isn't usually something they're focused on. They want to make sure they

00:04:18.600 --> 00:04:21.679
get the numbers out there, and they might have a JSON file or our state has

00:04:21.679 --> 00:04:24.799
an XML file. The media grabs that, and then the media does the really cool

00:04:24.799 --> 00:04:27.559
visualization part. You know, I've gone to the New York Times for my election

00:04:27.559 --> 00:04:30.440
results. I've gone to CNN. I'm sure a lot of you have as well, because they have

00:04:30.440 --> 00:04:34.679
really cool results, and they have interactive maps. A lot of states don't.

00:04:34.679 --> 00:04:40.000
Idaho had never used maps for official election results. You know, being an

00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:44.279
election junkie myself, in this current job and previously, I had looked at a lot

00:04:44.279 --> 00:04:47.839
of historical results and visualized them and created really fun interactive

00:04:47.880 --> 00:04:54.920
maps, but I had never done it, you know, we wanted to incorporate that in the

00:04:54.920 --> 00:04:58.839
actual official ones, and obviously we have access in R to all kinds of cool

00:04:58.839 --> 00:05:03.959
mapping packages, things that create beautiful tables, and so I wanted to

00:05:03.959 --> 00:05:11.040
leverage that expertise, but then also have it update in real time and be a

00:05:11.040 --> 00:05:14.880
resource for people on election night. So the only problem with the New York Times,

00:05:14.880 --> 00:05:18.519
I already mentioned I'm a data team of one, right? My position never existed

00:05:18.519 --> 00:05:22.959
before. I'm about to double my number by bringing in Dr. Andrew Heiss. The only

00:05:22.959 --> 00:05:25.920
problem with the New York Times is they have more than one person. I'm sure

00:05:25.920 --> 00:05:29.799
that's a huge surprise to hear, but this is 2020. This is just the Idaho election

00:05:29.799 --> 00:05:34.679
results page, and if you scroll to the bottom of this page, they credit over 40

00:05:34.679 --> 00:05:38.519
people on working on just Idaho's election results, and I didn't know it at

00:05:38.519 --> 00:05:42.959
the time, but 2024 obviously is what we're gonna end up competing against.

00:05:42.959 --> 00:05:50.040
They had 63 people listed as working on that, which tells me a couple things, but

00:05:50.040 --> 00:05:55.279
most importantly, you know, it shows the New York Times was also taking 2024 more

00:05:55.279 --> 00:05:59.679
seriously and realizing there's a lot more attention and scrutiny, and that's

00:05:59.679 --> 00:06:02.320
just for Idaho, right? Not a lot of people go to New York Times for Idaho's

00:06:02.320 --> 00:06:06.399
election results, especially in the presidential. It's usually a

00:06:06.399 --> 00:06:09.880
foregone conclusion. Idaho hasn't voted for a Democratic presidential candidate

00:06:09.880 --> 00:06:17.559
since 1964. Okay, in terms of timeline, so I've already mentioned it needs to be

00:06:17.559 --> 00:06:21.359
perfectly accurate, right? Otherwise, it's January 6th at my house. I already

00:06:21.359 --> 00:06:24.480
mentioned, you know, it needs to be visually appealing because we want

00:06:24.480 --> 00:06:28.920
people to go to our site, go to the source, rather than just go to, you know,

00:06:28.920 --> 00:06:32.679
other organizations, and we want election results that Idahoans can be proud of and

00:06:32.679 --> 00:06:37.079
confident in, but there's this other constraint, which is the timeline. So our

00:06:37.079 --> 00:06:43.839
NewVoteIdaho.gov website launched in February of 2024. The election's not till

00:06:43.839 --> 00:06:47.799
November, so I've got quite a few months to work on this, right? Now, the general

00:06:47.799 --> 00:06:50.480
election for our non-U.S. friends, this is the one you always see in the news

00:06:50.480 --> 00:06:57.279
where president is up. The only issue is, I keep saying the only issue is, there's

00:06:57.279 --> 00:07:03.760
lots of issues here, as you can tell. In Idaho, we have the primary election on

00:07:03.760 --> 00:07:09.359
May 21st, and so a primary election is where Democrats face off against

00:07:09.359 --> 00:07:13.160
Democrats, Republicans face off against Republicans, and then the ones who win

00:07:13.160 --> 00:07:17.079
within their party then go on the ballot for November. The primary election in

00:07:17.079 --> 00:07:21.679
Idaho is more important than the November election because the Republicans

00:07:21.679 --> 00:07:26.079
and Republican districts are likely to win in November, and the Democrats and

00:07:26.079 --> 00:07:29.440
Democratic districts are likely to win in November. So that's where all the

00:07:29.440 --> 00:07:32.760
attention is, that's where all the money is. We have a ton of cool campaign

00:07:32.760 --> 00:07:35.920
finance data you can go look at to prove that all the money is spent in May,

00:07:35.920 --> 00:07:41.640
and there's more eyeballs on May, and unfortunately that is fast approaching

00:07:41.640 --> 00:07:46.839
at this point. Another challenge we have is, you know, the New York Times is

00:07:46.839 --> 00:07:50.279
showing kind of the nationally relevant races, like President and Congress. We

00:07:50.279 --> 00:07:54.880
have to show those and the legislative ones, the ballot measures, and then all

00:07:54.880 --> 00:07:58.559
the local stuff, because as the official place to go for election results, we

00:07:58.559 --> 00:08:02.720
can't just show the ones that seem interesting. We have to show them all. So

00:08:02.720 --> 00:08:07.480
we have over 400 races in May that we have to show, and I mentioned the

00:08:07.480 --> 00:08:11.640
accuracy part, right? You can't say 99.9 percent uptime like you guys usually do

00:08:11.640 --> 00:08:17.200
in the data science world. You know, if 399 are right and one's wrong, like that

00:08:17.200 --> 00:08:20.119
person that's in that race is watching that page and they're gonna notice, and

00:08:20.119 --> 00:08:25.320
they're gonna take a screenshot. So our results, they also have to update in real

00:08:25.320 --> 00:08:28.119
time. So unlike all the data analysis that a lot of us have done in the room, I

00:08:28.160 --> 00:08:33.159
know my experience working with our data, you know, you have a static data set, it

00:08:33.159 --> 00:08:36.760
may be super messy, it may be clean, whatever, but it's like static. Or we've

00:08:36.760 --> 00:08:40.119
had data that updates daily, but never every few minutes, right? So as the

00:08:40.119 --> 00:08:43.719
results are coming in, we can't just wait till the end of the night to show it.

00:08:43.719 --> 00:08:49.479
That's also how conspiracy theories start. Where are all the results? So we

00:08:49.479 --> 00:08:53.320
we need it to update in real time. So that's kind of the real challenge

00:08:53.479 --> 00:08:58.640
at this point, you know, kind of figuring out all these other things. How do we get

00:08:58.640 --> 00:09:03.520
it to update in real time? And so I bring on Dr. Andrew Heist, professor at Georgia

00:09:03.520 --> 00:09:06.080
State here in Atlanta. A lot of you probably know him from his great blog

00:09:06.080 --> 00:09:11.280
posts and YouTube videos. He's just really cool dude, so come talk to him. So

00:09:11.280 --> 00:09:20.000
I brought him on. We met 40 days before the primary election. So we're given

00:09:20.000 --> 00:09:22.840
these timeline constraints and all the other constraints I've mentioned. We

00:09:22.840 --> 00:09:27.599
don't necessarily have time to learn new tools to reincorporate this

00:09:27.599 --> 00:09:30.200
workflow. You know, we're really comfortable working in R. If you've used

00:09:30.200 --> 00:09:34.320
Cordo, you know it's a great product for publishing your visuals. We wanted to

00:09:34.320 --> 00:09:38.520
stay with something that's familiar. So, you know, I'm proud to

00:09:38.520 --> 00:09:43.599
report we were able to do this whole project without ever leaving RStudio. We

00:09:43.599 --> 00:09:46.359
didn't, you know, we didn't need a separate process for SQL, and we didn't

00:09:46.359 --> 00:09:49.000
need a separate process for like publishing the website, and then of

00:09:49.000 --> 00:09:52.440
course all the data wrangling and visualization in the middle. We all were

00:09:52.440 --> 00:09:58.559
able to do within the R ecosystem. Okay, so I've listed a bunch of challenges. If

00:09:58.559 --> 00:10:03.719
you're not freaked out yet, before I turn it over to Andrew to kind of show some

00:10:03.719 --> 00:10:08.000
of the cool stuff he figured out for the data pipeline, I just wanted to show you

00:10:08.000 --> 00:10:11.159
a quick preview of the final product so you're not sitting there wondering, man,

00:10:11.159 --> 00:10:13.280
did these guys actually pull this thing off? I'm not sure they're going to be

00:10:13.280 --> 00:10:21.239
able to do it. So this was the November 24 election. This was our most basic page,

00:10:21.239 --> 00:10:25.400
which is just the presidential race, but one thing that's, there's a few things

00:10:25.400 --> 00:10:28.960
that were really exciting about using Cordo for this project. Having the

00:10:28.960 --> 00:10:31.960
different district types at the top for navigation was a huge win for our state,

00:10:31.960 --> 00:10:35.159
and a lot of other states, you know, you don't usually don't have that kind of

00:10:35.159 --> 00:10:38.039
ease of navigation. You're usually having all the races on one page and having to

00:10:38.039 --> 00:10:41.159
scroll through, which is also why people seek out the media who have kind of

00:10:41.159 --> 00:10:44.919
thought these things through a little better. You know, having the status bar at

00:10:44.919 --> 00:10:48.119
the top to show whether results were official or unofficial. I'm not sure if

00:10:48.119 --> 00:10:51.239
you can see it, but there's a call-out block that's in green that says 44 of 44

00:10:51.239 --> 00:10:53.799
counties are reported. That updated throughout the night, so every few

00:10:53.799 --> 00:10:57.599
minutes as the results are coming in, people were able to use that drop-down,

00:10:57.599 --> 00:11:00.719
figure out who's still coming and not, and then once the bar is green, you know

00:11:00.719 --> 00:11:06.640
there's not going to be any more results coming in. So real quick, the, you know,

00:11:06.640 --> 00:11:13.039
you have kind of the race breakdown here. It's a Reactable, Reactable with a

00:11:13.039 --> 00:11:17.880
nice spark bar, and then for every race you have kind of the raw results summed,

00:11:17.880 --> 00:11:23.359
like you can see there, and then a tab that has a map. So for every one of the

00:11:23.359 --> 00:11:27.840
400 races, there was a map, and we love leaflet maps and they're interactive, and

00:11:27.840 --> 00:11:30.159
you know, we know all the exciting things about them, but it was really cool to

00:11:30.159 --> 00:11:33.159
have those kind of updating throughout the night. And then another thing that's

00:11:33.159 --> 00:11:36.440
great about Cordo, as you guys know, is the table of contents. They were able to

00:11:36.440 --> 00:11:39.039
throw on the left, so being able to jump between district without having to

00:11:39.039 --> 00:11:45.080
scroll up and down is huge, especially with as many races as we had. Real quick,

00:11:45.080 --> 00:11:50.280
so the, you know, leaflet, I learned a really cool thing, and we'll have a repo

00:11:50.280 --> 00:11:54.320
at the end where you can check it out, but the tooltips for leaflet, you can

00:11:54.320 --> 00:11:59.960
actually use custom HTML within a column and then just call to that for

00:11:59.960 --> 00:12:03.359
the pop-up, and so that was able to kind of programmatically regenerate

00:12:03.359 --> 00:12:08.719
every time the results came in as well. All right, finally, on the website, this

00:12:08.719 --> 00:12:13.359
was something new we did November, not for May, which was really cool. If we had

00:12:13.359 --> 00:12:17.159
not done any of the other stuff I showed you, but just did this, we would

00:12:17.159 --> 00:12:21.719
have gotten a lot of credit in our state. We created this close races page that

00:12:21.719 --> 00:12:25.599
dynamically, every time the site updated, was checking to see which races were

00:12:25.599 --> 00:12:30.159
close, as the name implies. You know, what's funny about this is my boss and I,

00:12:30.159 --> 00:12:34.679
you know, the Secretary of State being a data nerd as he is, we went back and

00:12:34.679 --> 00:12:37.520
forth on what the threshold should be, what's a close race. I looked at some

00:12:37.520 --> 00:12:40.239
historical races and I thought, you know, three percentage points would be a great

00:12:40.280 --> 00:12:44.200
margin. I thought, you know, a nice balance of not having too many races, but it's not

00:12:44.200 --> 00:12:47.840
empty, and he thought, no, it really should be like eight percentage points. We

00:12:47.840 --> 00:12:51.679
need a wider net, and so we went back and forth on this, and I, you know, is any

00:12:51.679 --> 00:12:54.520
great compromise with your boss? We ended up going with his number, the eight

00:12:54.520 --> 00:12:59.359
percentage points, but he was right. If we had gone with my threshold, there

00:12:59.359 --> 00:13:01.559
only would have been one race on this page at the end of the night, and we

00:13:01.559 --> 00:13:04.200
ended up having about half a dozen, but when we're kind of following the

00:13:04.200 --> 00:13:08.799
analytics on election night, this is the page everybody was looking at, which was

00:13:09.239 --> 00:13:14.239
really cool, and we got a lot of credit for it. Okay, so before I turn it over to

00:13:14.239 --> 00:13:19.400
Andrew, if we're thinking about, you know, like an organization like the New York

00:13:19.400 --> 00:13:22.000
Times, where these people are doing really cool stuff. Yeah, they have 63 people, but

00:13:22.000 --> 00:13:24.760
they're really kind of divided into three roles. You got the data engineers

